He has shown that many aspects of African design -- in architecture, art, even hair braiding -- are based on perfect fractal patterns.", "whylisten": "

"Ethno-mathematician" Ron Eglash is the author of African Fractals, a book that examines the fractal patterns underpinning architecture, art and design in many parts of Africa. By looking at aerial-view photos -- and then following up with detailed research on the ground -- Eglash discovered that many African villages are purposely laid out to form perfect fractals, with self-similar shapes repeated in the rooms of the house, and the house itself, and the clusters of houses in the village, in mathematically predictable patterns.

As he puts it: "When Europeans first came to Africa, they considered the architecture very disorganized and thus primitive. It never occurred to them that the Africans might have been using a form of mathematics that they hadn't even discovered yet."

His other areas of study are equally fascinating, including research into African and Native American cybernetics, teaching kids math through culturally specific design tools (such as the Virtual Breakdancer applet, which explores rotation and sine functions), and race and ethnicity issues in science and technology. Eglash teaches in the Department of Science and Technology Studies at Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute in New York, and he recently co-edited the book Appropriating Technology, about how we reinvent consumer tech for our own uses.

aws-transcripts.transcript: I want to start my story in Germany. In 18 77 the mathematician named George Cantor and Cantor decided he was gonna take a line and erased the middle third of the line and then take those two resulting lines and bring them back into the same process of recursive process. So he starts out with one line and then two and then four, then 16. So and if he does, there's an infinite number of times what you can do in mathematics. He ends up with an infinite number of lines, each of which has an infinite number of points in it. So he realized he had a set whose number of elements was larger than infinity, and this blew his mind literally. He checked in the sanitarium, and when it came out of the sanitarium, he was convinced that he had been put on Earth to found trance finite set theory because the largest set of infinity would be God himself was very religious, man. It's a mathematician on a mission, and other mathematicians did the same sort of thing. Swedish mathematician von Coke decided that instead of subtracting lines, he would add them, and so he came up with this beautiful curve. And there's no particular reason why we have to start with this seed shape. We can use any, uh, any seed shape we like. And, uh, rearrange this and I'll stick this somewhere down there. Okay? And, uh, now upon it oration, that seed shape sort of unfolds into a very different looking structure. So these all have the property of self similarity. The part looks like the holes, the same pattern at many different scales. Now, mathematicians thought this was very strange because as you shrink a ruler down, you measure a longer and longer length. And since they went through the generations an infinite number of times As the ruler shrinks down to infinity, the length goes to infinity.
